revision.text:
[[File:Perforated baton with low relief horse.jpg|thumb|[[Baton fragment (Palart 310)|Perforated baton with low relief horse]], from the Abri de la Madeleine, [[British Museum]].]] [[File:Cro-Magnon.jpg|thumb|upright|A Cro-Magnon skull.]] The '''Abri de la Madeleine''' (Magdalene Shelter) is a prehistoric shelter under an overhanging cliff situated near [[Tursac]], in the [[Dordogne]] département and the [[Aquitaine]] Région of South-Western France. The [[Magdalenian]] culture of the [[Upper Paleolithic]] is named after it, as the [[type site]].<ref>Brian M. Fagan, Leo S. Klejn, Keith N. Schoville, Ian Morris, Douglas R. Givens "History of Archaeology Before 1900" The Oxford Companion to Archaeology. Brian M. Fagan, ed., Oxford University Press 1996. Oxford Reference Online. Oxford University Press. 30 October 2011.</ref> Prehistoric finds from the site include the [[Bison Licking Insect Bite]], a carving estimated [[20,000 BC in art|20,000 BC]]. The shelter was reoccupied during the [[Middle Ages]]. The medieval castle of Petit Marsac stands on the top of the cliff just above the shelter.
==Excavations== [[Édouard Lartet]] & [[Henry Christy]] were the first systematic excavators of the site, and published their findings in 1875 as the [[Age of the Reindeer]] ("L'âge du renne"). Finds from '''la Madeleine''' are distributed among a number of museums, including the [[Muséum de Toulouse]], the [[National Archaeological Museum (France)|Musee des Antiquites Nationales]], [[St. Germain-en-Laye]] and the [[British Museum]].
